  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The publication \"The Belgian Photonovel, 1954-1985\" marks a significant scholarly contribution to the understanding of the photonovel genre, highlighting its cultural and artistic relevance in Belgium during a transformative period. Despite a lack of immediate citations and public discourse, its association with major commercial platforms suggests a potential for broader societal engagement.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">\"The Belgian Photonovel, 1954-1985\" offers an in-depth exploration of a unique cultural phenomenon that has largely gone unexamined in academic literature. Published by Leuven University Press in 2023, this book examines the intersection of photography and narrative art in Belgium, providing context and analysis that enrich the understanding of visual storytelling within a specific historical framework. While currently cited figures are minimal, indicating an early stage in scholarly uptake, the book is listed on significant commercial platforms such as Amazon and Goodreads, pointing to its potential reach and interest among both academic and general audiences.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The absence of social media discussions or mentions in high-fidelity platforms such as Wikipedia, Reddit, or Bluesky may initially suggest limited public engagement; however, this also implies an opportunity for future discourse and outreach, especially in a field that grapples with evolving media forms. The limited citations reflect the beginning of academic interest, yet the book is positioned within a niche topic that invites further exploration and critical engagement.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The work's strength is its potential to foster a deeper understanding of cultural narratives and their implications in society. It touches on themes that align with sustainable policies, evidenced by a quantifiable link to one of the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs). This connection may encourage its use in interdisciplinary discussions that extend beyond traditional humanities boundaries and into contemporary discourse on media and communication's societal impact.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">As the academic landscape continues to evolve, this publication stands as a foundational research output, poised to inform future scholarship on photographic literature. It presents an invitation to researchers and students alike to engage with the past and present of photonovels, encouraging a revival of interest in this art form and potentially enhancing its visibility in both academic and public spheres.</p>",
